### Instruction: 

 Define 'company in which the public are substantially interested' as per the Income-tax Act, 1961.

### Response: 

 A company in which the public are substantially interested includes: 
(a) A company owned by the Government or the Reserve Bank of India, or in which at least 40% of shares are held by the Government, RBI, or a corporation owned by RBI; 
(aa) A company registered under section 25 of the Companies Act, 1956; 
(ab) A company with no share capital, declared by the Board to be a company in which the public are substantially interested; 
(ac) A mutual benefit finance company declared by the Central Government to be a Nidhi or Mutual Benefit Society under section 620A of the Companies Act, 1956; 
(ad) A company where at least 50% of voting power shares are held by one or more co-operative societies.
